These notions are not unique to FRBR, of course, and writings by Levy, Skare, Tanselle, P. Wilson and Nunberg (among a great many others) have, I think, often expressed them better than the FRBR report does (and Frohmann has critiqued some of these ideas). Often the grouping is work - text - document.

Perhaps it would be useful to note, at some point, that these are not inventions of the FRBR report (or of cataloguing more widely), and have a much wider literature and discussion supporting them.

